post_text:
Attention OA families:

The Genesee-Orleans Ministry of Concern is collecting and distributing school supplies for students/families with extenuating financial needs.

If you'd like to either donate supplies, or receive them, please call (585) 589-9210 and ask for Ayesha Kreutz.

According to the information they provided, "All supplies are given on a first come-first-serve basis until supplies have run out, so please have people call to make arrangements as soon as possible. Upon request, it is possible for us to drop off bags of supplies to schools, if there are multiple students in need, if preferred. "

IMPORTANT INFO:

To all parents of children in the middle and high school, this is typically when schedules would be mailed home but they are not quite completed... Mr. Peterson sent an envelope of information home today but it did not include the schedules. Students and parents can get a glimpse of the schedules (as they exist now) on SchoolTool with the understanding that some minor changes might take place between now and when school opens‚Ä¶ by making the schedules available on SchoolTool it should help parents as they shop for school supplies. The Parent Lighthouse Team needs your help! Even in these uncertain times, the School Supply Drive will help support some of our students go back to school prepared to succeed whether at school, in person, or working remotely. We are looking to collect just under 30 bags of school supplies for some of our district students.

There are two different ways you can help:

üíô ‚ÄúSponsor‚Äù a student bag (purchase all of the needed supplies for a specific grade)

Or

üíõ Purchase some of the materials on the list so we can build the bag of supplies

If interested in helping, please comment below or message us!

Thank you for your help! üíôüíõ

post_text:
The Spring 2020 baseball season was one that our coaches and players were looking forward to and were really excited about. Led by our returning seniors Joey Burdick, Ryan Manges, and Aiden Johnston with the addition of our two juniors Peyton Yasses and Ty Kornow, this team was looking forward to the opportunity to make some noise in the league. These boys had put in many pre-season hours on Tuesday morning open gyms to work on swing technique, pitching strength and accuracy, and position specific skills. We were ready and thrilled to debut our new uniforms and to host our first annual OA Varsity Baseball Tournament featuring great talent from around the area. Needless to say, our athletes lost a great opportunity to play their spring sports this season and our seniors lost their last chance to play a game for the blue and gold. We, as a program, will look forward to the future, to summer baseball, to off-season training, to learning about life in our new normal, and to the return of sports!

Oakfield-Alabama Hornets Baseball
text:
The Spring 2020 baseball season was one that our coaches and players were looking forward to and were really excited about. Led by our returning seniors Joey Burdick, Ryan Manges, and Aiden Johnston with the addition of our two juniors Peyton Yasses and Ty Kornow, this team was looking forward to the opportunity to make some noise in the league. These boys had put in many pre-season hours on Tuesday morning open gyms to work on swing technique, pitching strength and accuracy, and position specific skills. We were ready and thrilled to debut our new uniforms and to host our first annual OA Varsity Baseball Tournament featuring great talent from around the area. Needless to say, our athletes lost a great opportunity to play their spring sports this season and our seniors lost their last chance to play a game for the blue and gold. We, as a program, will look forward to the future, to summer baseball, to off-season training, to learning about life in our new normal, and to the return of sports!

Oakfield-Alabama Hornets Baseball

OA Graduation will be held June 20th at 11am; however, due to our current situation, the campus will be closed to anyone other than the graduate and his/her immediate family. A detailed letter has been shared with our seniors (check your email and a hard copy will be mailed home as well). The district will be broadcasting the ceremony on WBTA radio station along with a recording, in addition to the posting of a video for viewing at a later time.

We recognize our OA community wants to honor and celebrate our seniors, so we are in the process of organizing a parade to follow immediately after the ceremony. The route will be shared once it's finalized so you can safely cheer on our graduates.

post_text:
ATTENTION Elementary Families:

Our elementary building will be open Tuesday, May 19th and Thursday, May 21st to pick up your child's belongings. The times for both days are as follows: 9am-11am UPK and First grade, 12pm-2pm Kindergarten, Second and Fourth grade, and 4pm-5pm Third and Fifth grade items will be available.

Please enter through the elementary main doors; all items will be labeled in the gym. We will have a separate entrance and exit, tables will be spaced apart, and we encourage you to bring your own mask as we follow the social distancing guidelines. If you have multiple children please pick a time that works for your schedule to collect all their items at once.

Lastly, we will have a bin located in the gym to return any of the library books you have borrowed. If you have any questions or concerns please contact me directly at LGehlert@oahornets.org.

Elementary Parents-
The Parent Lighthouse Team needs your help! May is when we typically celebrate Teacher, Bus Driver, and Staff Appreciation Day at OA. We need to celebrate a little differently. Town of Oakfield
March 21 at 2:59 PM ¬∑

In accordance with the Oakfield Town Supervisor and the Oakfield Town Board, it has been decided that during the Coronavirus crisis, we are offering to the ELDERLY and DISABLED residents in the Town & Village of Oakfield the following service:

Volunteers will get FOOD and ESSENTIAL household items for those in need. The items will be delivered to your home at which time payment is mandatory (cash or check only). Volunteers will purchase items with their own money so please be prepared to pay them when the items are delivered.
Our volunteers will practice Personal Protection for both you and themselves. They will not be entering the home, just delivering to the door, with minimal contact and collecting the funds for the purchases.

If you are in need of this service, please contact the Oakfield Town Office at 948-5835 ext. 101, Monday-Thursday 9:00-4:00 and leave a message. A volunteer will return your call as soon as possible.

Attention Sports Fans!

As per Section V rules, all sites that host sectional contests must charge $5 admission fee for boys and girls basketball.

Oakfield-Alabama will host girls' basketball games on Wednesday February 26th (Pembroke vs Sodus at 5:30pm and Oakfield-Alabama vs Alexander at 7pm) and a boys' basketball game on Friday February 28th at 7pm (Oakfield-Alabama vs winner of South Seneca vs Naples).

In accordance with Section V rules, we will have to charge the $5 admission fee on both nights. Please plan accordingly.

Capital Improvement Project Information

Voting will take place: Wednesday, March 18th from 11:00am-8:00pm in the Community Room.

At the January Board of Education meeting, the Board approved a $15.3M Capital Project for OA. Subsequently, District residents will vote to approve this Capital Project work on Wednesday, March 18th from 11:00am-8:00pm in the Community Room. As required by New York State, OA conducted a Building Conditions Survey over this past summer into fall to prioritize the necessary work our buildings, grounds, and campus needed in order to maintain our facilities. The focus of the work centers on student safety, upgrading building code and ADA requirements, and the replacement or repair of equipment throughout the District.

Please see file below for more information and details of the project.

On Monday, November 25th students are invited to participate in fundraising for the O-A faculty team participating in the Polar Plunge in December. All donations will go to support the Special Olympics athletes of NY. For $1 students in the elementary school are invited to wear a hat. In the Middle/High School students are invited to wear pajamas with their $1 donation. Students will receive snowflake stickers to wear to thank them for their donations.

If families, friends, and community members would like to offer additional support to the O-A team they can do so at the following link:
http://events.nyso.org/site/TR/Plunge/POLARPLUNGE?team_id=7300&pg=team&fr_id=1750

The O-A Polar Plunge team thanks everyone for supporting our Special Olympics athletes as we look forward to upcoming events for our team!

post_text:
There is still time to drop off your clean plastic bags!!

OA Families and Community...The LIVE Program once again is collecting clean plastic shopping bags to donate to a group called Mats for a Mission. They take old shopping bags and turn them into mats for the homeless. You can drop off your bags here at the high school until December 11th or contact Mrs. Boreanaz at the school. We will be having a speaker from Mats for a Mission on December 12th from 9:30-10:30 if you are interested in hearing what they do and how you can help.

We are also collecting old crayons that we will be recycling into new chunk letters which will be available for purchase from any of the LIVE students or in our school store located in Rm. 161 in the high school . Crayons can also be dropped off at the high school or contact Mrs. Boreanaz for pick up.

Please share this post so we can collect as many bags and crayons as we can before the Christmas season.

The OA Varsity Club is holding the Activity Night tonight at the Middle High School.
Grades 1-5 will be held from 3:30-5:30. The elementary children will be escorted up to the high school by the Varsity Club members. Grades 6-8 will be held from 5:45-8:00. A $5 donation will be accepted to participate. Walk-ins are accepted. There will be concessions available for purchase, as well.

Activities offered include games in both sides of the gym, scooter racing, dancing in the cafeteria, Wii room games and an obstacle course.

Unfortunately, a problem has arisen with the pool pump and swimming will not be an option for the children. We apologize profusely for this unexpected change. If your child was set on coming in to swim and does not want to attend, we can refund any money that was collected. If this is the case, contact Mrs. Harkness at 948-5211 x 4514 or Mr. Stehlar at 948-5211 x3009.

We hope that they will still want to come and participate in the other activities that are offered.

post_text: The OAE cheerleaders went to cheer on the walkers at the Alzheimer's walk in Batavia on September 21st 2019. These girls lined at the nursing home after cheering on the OAE football team the night before. The cheerleaders had a fun time and could be heard saying things like, "Coming here is fun" or "The hotdogs are great!" The walkers seemed to enjoy them being there and the cheerleaders love seeing the smile on the walker's faces. They thought it was the greatest thing to go cheer on walkers for something so important. It is truly amazing. Many walkers joined in on the cheers after hearing them. It's an experience to go be apart of for sure!!

TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT

Genesee County Emergency Management Services
June 19, 2019 at 7:15 PM ¬∑

Emergency services careers were highlighted at this years Oakfield Alabama Elementary School Career Day. Emergency Management joined with Genesee County Dispatch, Oakfield Fire department and Mercy EMS to demonstrate the various careers in Emergency services. A simulated student emergency escalated from the nurses office, to 911 and a fire department and ambulance response. The presentation was capped off with a tour of several emergency service vehicles. Thank you to the Genesee Business Education Alliance for the invitation to participate in the event and all of the staff at OASC

post_text: Are you a local business owner/ manager in the OA community or surrounding area? If so, the LIVE Program (Learning Independence with Vocational Experiences) is looking for your help. We are creating a Business Advisory Board for the program and need local businesses to be part of the board. If you want to help shape the next generation workforce please consider coming to this introductory meeting on June 26th from 9-10am in the OA Community Room located in the High School. A light breakfast will be provided. Please RSVP by June 24th to Nicole Boreanaz at nboreanaz@oahornets.org or (585)948-5211 ext 4501.
